##New Crown Vaccine R & D competition is in full swing, different technical routes who has more play?

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to clear the fog, to seek the truth, to watch the Times.

"when an outbreak hits the headlines, the government spends money on research.

But as soon as the news of the epidemic disappeared, the funding for the research disappeared."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The first clinical trial of a new coronavirus vaccine was conducted in Seattle (picture: CBS screenshot) 

On January 10,2020, just three hours after Chinese scientist Zhang Yongzhen announced the genetic sequence of the new coronavirus to the world, a new vaccine was designed by the US Vaccine Research and Development Company Inovio laboratories in a computer-based genetic sequencing software, and announced that human clinical trials would begin as soon as this summer. This was once considered one of the fastest vaccine development records of the century, but it is now being broken in terms of the time it has taken to get to clinical trials.

On March 16, scientists at the CӒSAR permanent Washington Institute in Seattle, United States, injected the first of four healthy volunteers with the experimental new Crown Vaccine. The vaccine, code named mRNA-1273, was developed by the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Disease in conjunction with MODERNA. The latter specializes in messenger RNA based vaccines.

On March 17, a day after the American trial vaccine was injected into the subjects, Tianjin Kangxinuo Biological Co. announced that it had developed the Adenovirus vector vaccine in cooperation with the Institute of Bioengineering of the Chinese Academy of Military Medicine, preparations for the clinical trial and the recruitment of subjects have begun. The morning of the 18th, Konsino announced that the candidate vaccine has been approved to enter clinical trials. The team, led by Chen Wei, a researcher at the Chinese Academy of Military Sciences and an engineer, is now China's fastest vaccine developer.

According to incomplete statistics, as of March 8, the world has about 64 new coronavirus vaccine research projects, of which China alone and cooperation with other countries a total of 36 projects. A global race to develop a vaccine is under way.

Five major technical routes to develop vaccines

Zhang Linqi, director of the Center for Global Health and Infectious Diseases at Tsinghua University, who was involved in the Mers vaccine development, explained that the principle behind the new vaccine is to induce antibodies that are highly neutralizing to the virus, this is one of the most important goals of any vaccine strategy right now. But in this race, the means to get there are different.

China has laid out five technical routes for the development of a new crown vaccine, it includes inactivated vaccine, genetically engineered subunit vaccine, Adenovirus vector vaccine, attenuated influenza vector vaccine and DNA based nucleic acid vaccine. Among them, the inactivated vaccine and the attenuated influenza virus vector vaccine did not see the global other countries have the related report, the other three and the Foreign Research and development basic synchronization. However, since there is no precedent for conducting clinical trials of Mrna vaccines in China, some Foreign Research and development institutions may surpass China in future clinical trials.

On the afternoon of March 17, at a press conference of the joint prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council, Wang Junzhi, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, said that the vaccine in the five major technical directions was progressing smoothly in general, the first nine identified tasks have done most of the work on animals. Most of the research and development teams were able to complete preclinical studies and start clinical trials in April.

Tao Lina, a former immunologic planning doctor at the Shanghai Center for Disease Control and Prevention, told China News weekly that among the five methods, the inactivated vaccine was made by stimulating the immune system of healthy people with the killed virus, the other pathways are based on the same theory: The s protein on the virus causes the body's immune protection mechanism, so the vaccines are targeted at the s protein target. Genetically engineered subunit vaccines produce s protein in vitro, both adenovirus and nucleic acid techniques produce s protein in Vivo, and Adenovirus vector vaccines have been used in Ebola vaccines, approved but not actually used in humans, the nucleic acid vaccine is an entirely new technology that has never been used in humans.

Of the 51 new crown vaccine projects that have been announced globally, only six have used traditional inactivation or inactivation techniques, while viral vectors and Mrna vaccine techniques that have emerged in recent years are favored by researchers and developers. Meanwhile, Lei Chaozi, director of the Department of Science and Technology of the Ministry of Education, revealed on March 17 that research teams from universities including Xiamen University, Sichuan University, Tsinghua University, Peking University and Fudan University have all been involved in the vaccine challenge. He also pointed out that, the emphasis is on three technical routes of influenza virus vector vaccine, recombinant protein vaccine and nucleic acid vaccine.

China and the United States respectively made new progress in the two experimental vaccines, just belong to relatively new vaccine development technology. The technology used in clinical trials of vaccines in the United States is to design targeted mrnas based on the genetic sequence of the virus, known as the target, and then enter human cells through a delivery system that allows the immune system to recognize the virus, antibody production. The delivery system is the process of coating Mrna with a special shell, which fuses the shell with the cell membrane, allowing the pseudovirus to enter the body.

NIAID and MODERNA scientists had previously worked on a vaccine targeting the s protein in the MERS outbreak, the NIH said. Based on the Mers vaccine, they replaced the corresponding sequence with that of the new coronavirus, and then quickly produced a vaccine for the new coronavirus Mrna.

NIAID director Antony Foutch told China News weekly in February that advances in scientific understanding of coronavirus since the SARS outbreak in 2003 could significantly shorten the time it takes to develop a vaccine. So from getting the genetic sequence of the new coronavirus to a phase I clinical trial, he hopes the process can be shortened to three months. But now it turns out that the actual process was shorter than three months.

At one point in early March, Chinese Internet posts circulated a photo of "academician Chen Wei receiving the new PLA Academy of Military Science Vaccine, " which was later confirmed to be a fake, in fact a photo of Chen before she left for Wuhan, where she was injected with a drug to boost her immune system. However, the Adenovirus vector vaccine, which she led the scientific team to develop jointly with the company, is indeed the "seed player" of the Chinese delegation in this international competition. They were genetically engineered to express the COVID-19 s antigen using replication defective Adenovirus type 5 as a vector.

An employee at a vaccine development company said the Adenovirus was originally an icosahedron-shaped virus, with spikes on the ICOSAHEDRON after a new coronavirus gene was delivered to the virus. ADENOVIRUSES are inherently weak, so they can be used to carry the new coronavirus's spines into the body's immune system. But this is not an original idea. On February 5th J & J announced that it would use its Ebola platform, dubbed the ADENOVIRUS, to develop a new vaccine that would take at least eight months to manufacture.

The alliance between the Academy and the company is not the first collaboration between the two institutions. Registered in 2009 in Tianjin, kangxinuo biological, mainly engaged in human vaccine research and development and production, there are currently 15 vaccine products for pneumonia, tuberculosis, Zaire ebolavirus, meningitis, DPT and other diseases. In 2017, its joint Zaire ebolavirus vaccine, AD5 Ebov, was approved for registration, making China the third country in the world to successfully develop the Zaire ebolavirus vaccine.

It won't be operational for a year

Ding Sheng, dean of the School of Pharmacy at Tsinghua University and Director of the Center for Global Health Drug Research and development, said that the current methods of developing vaccines have their own characteristics in terms of producing reasonable immunogenicity, future production, safety, and so on, it's hard to compare the two.

The team, led by Zhiwei Chen, director of the Li Ka Shing Faculty of Medicine, is part of the new vaccine effort, which is based on a DNA based nucleic acid vaccine, in the animal test has been initially achieved a better immune effect, but also for clinical trials to prepare. It's too early to tell which vaccines will actually be used in humans, he told China News Weekly.

Global Competition for new coronavirus vaccine. (photo: CBS screenshot)

Chen Zhiwei pointed out that the advantages of MRNA NUCLEIC ACID vaccine is fast, simple preparation, only need to synthesize RNA and then expand production, but DNA and RNA based vaccine has not yet been officially approved for use in humans. One important reason is its effectiveness, the ability of the vaccine to induce and protect the immune system when it enters the body.

On the other hand, because there is no approved vaccine on the market, which means that the industrialization is not mature, follow-up can meet the tens of thousands of large-scale population application is also difficult. On Feb. 10, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, the Tongji University School of Medicine in Shanghai and SMB, a company based on the Mrna Platform, developed a new coronavirus vaccine that has already been started in animal trials and injected into more than 100 healthy mice. Li Hangwen, CEO of microbiotics, a leading domestic maker of MRNA technology, said in a media interview that one of the major challenges of the technology is mass production of Mrna, as China has previously been very weak in this area, there is no commercial production and supply of Mrna in the company, so it is necessary for the company to complete the production of Mrna by itself and to have a large-scale and stable production of MRNA supply chain.

An expert in the development of the new coronavirus vaccine told China news weekly that the country's most promising adenovirus vector vaccine also has some risks. In theory, about 80 percent of the Chinese population is positive for Adenovirus type 5, meaning most people have already been infected, and when the adenovirus enters the body again, the body's antibodies attack the vector rather than the s protein it expresses, to render the vaccine ineffective, which is often referred to as a vector-blocking effect, or pre-existing immunity.

In 2004, Merck developed the type 5 Adenovirus Vaccine, which was proven in aids to be neither effective in preventing infection nor reducing the viral load in the plasma of the carrier, long-term follow-up even found that people injected with the vaccine were at even higher risk of infection, a trial that failed in 2007 and became the biggest blow in the history of AIDS vaccine development.

Xu Jianqing is the director of the Institute of Medical Science and is also the head of the institute's Xinguan Vaccine Research and development team. He would not comment on the progress of the research, saying only that the human cell carrier vaccine technology they used was the first to be used to make a vaccine for an infectious disease.

Another HKU team's attenuated influenza vector vaccine may also have pre-existing immunity problems, depending on whether the chosen vector has been previously infected in humans, Tsui said. However, Chen argues that the vaccine has at least the distinct advantage of industrialisation -- as if there were many flu vaccine companies in the country, producing hundreds of millions of vaccine products a year once it became a success.

Taurina said that in terms of research and development, transgenic recombinant technology is relatively safe, and based on the technology of existing vaccines, which means that the development of off-the-shelf production lines, mass production will not be a problem. Among the teams using the technology, he thinks it is particularly noteworthy that the Chinese Academy of Sciences Institute of Microbiology has done a lot of basic work on the development of a coronavirus vaccine, in conjunction with Zhifei biology, which has had MERS vaccines in place since 2018.

However, even if Niaid, which is currently the world's fastest runner, takes three months to complete the first phase of the trial, it will take another three months to get the results and then move on to the second phase, Antony Foutch, the agency's director, told China News Weekly, clinical trials in a larger population. "Even if we get an emergency license, the vaccine is unlikely to be available in practice for at least a year. "

In past pandemics, the scientific community has been exploring how to balance speed and effectiveness, but in the face of a one-off pandemic, when fast and good R & D techniques have not yet been found, vaccines and drugs have always been in a quandary. For example, more than a decade ago, a vaccine against the SARS virus has yet to hit the market. Dingsheng said that there were initial advances in the SARS vaccine and some human trials, but since there were no patients, no one invested in it, it was difficult to carry out.

What will happen to the new Crown Vaccine? 'If the outbreak lasts long, the efficacy of the vaccine will be evaluated, ' Zhang said. 'If the outbreak is over, we can do a phase I clinical trial to prove the safety of the vaccine in case new coronaviruses come back in the future, to the protective evaluation phase as soon as possible.

Poland, the head of a Vaccine Institute in the United States, commented, "when the epidemic hit the headlines, the government threw money at research. But as soon as the news of the epidemic disappeared, the funding for research disappeared. " After Chen thanked SARS, with NIH funding, he was able to continue the research, and 17 years later, when the new coronavirus struck again, his experience came in Handy. He said that the country in peacetime how to carry out effective scientific research funding and technology reserve, is a question that requires policy makers to think carefully.
